1 7. The fitness to proceed examination must occur within fifteen days from receipt of
2 materials identified in subsections 4 and 5 and notice of entry of the order served on
3 the tier 1a mental health professional .
4 a. The court may grant an additional seven days to complete the examination if
5 good cause is shown.
6 b. The materials required in subsections 4 and 5 must be disclosed
7 contemporaneously with the order.
8 c. The tier 1a mental health professional shall notify the court and request any
9 missing or additional information within seventy-two hours of receiving this
10 information, and the attorneys and juvenile court staff have seven days to send
11 the information to the tier 1a mental health professional .
12 8. A tier 1a mental health professional who conducts a fitness to proceed examination
13 shall submit a written report to the court no later than fifteen days from completing the
14 fitness to proceed examination. The report must include:
15 a. A description of the nature, content, and extent of the examination, including:
16 (1) A description of the assessment procedure, technique, and test used;
17 (2) Medical, educational, and court records reviewed; and
18 (3) Social, clinical, developmental, and available legal history.
19 b. A clinical assessment that includes:
20 (1) A mental status examination;
21 (2) The diagnosis and functional impact of mental illness, developmental
22 disability, or cognitive impairment. If the minor is taking medication, the
23 impact of the medication on the minor's mental state and behavior;
24 (3) An assessment of the minor's intelligence and maturity level, when relevant;
25 (4) The minor's age, developmental state, and decisionmaking abilities; and
26 (5) Whether the minor has any other factor that affects fitness to proceed.
27 c. A description of abilities and deficits in the following mental competency functions
28 related to the minor's fitness to proceed:
29 (1) The ability to factually and rationally understand and appreciate the nature
30 and object of the proceedings, including the ability to:
